{{Infobox person |name=Edward Alexander Bouchet |image=Edward Alexander Bouchet Yale College class of 1874.jpg |caption= | birth_date = {{birth date|1852|9|15|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[New Haven, Connecticut]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1918|10|28|1852|9|15|mf=y}} | death_place = [[New Haven, Connecticut]] | nationality = African American | occupation = {{unbulleted list|[[Physicist]]|[[Professor]]}} | alma_mater = [[Yale University]] <small>(PhD) }}
'''Edward Alexander Bouchet''' (September 15, 1852 – October 28, 1918) was an [[African Americans|African American]] [[physicist]] and educator and was the first African-American to earn a [[Ph.D.]] from any American university, completing his [[dissertation]] in [[physics]] at [[Yale University|Yale]] in 1876. On the basis of his academic record he was elected to the [[Phi Beta Kappa Society]]. In 1874, he had become one of the first African Americans to graduate from Yale College.{{efn|He was long thought to have been the first African-American graduate of Yale College, but investigations made public in 2014 suggest that that distinction actually belongs to Richard Henry Green, who was awarded his bachelor of arts degree in 1857,<ref name =NYT>{{Citation | last = Kaminer | first = Ariel | title = Discovery Leads Yale to Revise a Chapter of Its Black History | newspaper = The New York Times | publication-place = New York, New York | volume = | issue = | date = February 28, 2014 | page = | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/01/nyregion/discovery-leads-yale-to-revise-a-chapter-of-its-black-history.html?hp }}</ref><ref name =YAM>{{Citation | last1 = Bass | first1 = Carole | last2 = Branch | first2 = Mark Alden | title = Yale College's first black grad: it's not who you think | magazine = Yale Alumni Magazine | publication-place = New Haven, Connecticut | volume = LXXVII| issue = 4 | date = March 2014 | page = | url = http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/blog_posts/1719 }}</ref> or possibly to Randall Lee Gibson or Moses Simons.<ref name =YAM2>{{Citation | last1 = Branch | first1 = Mark Alden | title = Before Green and Bouchet, another African American Yale College Grad. Maybe. | magazine = Yale Alumni Magazine | publication-place = New Haven, Connecticut | volume = | issue = | date = 7 March 2014 | page = | url = http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/blog_posts/1729 }}</ref>}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.ams.org/samplings/math-history/hmath3-index|title=A Century of Mathematics in America|date=1988-1989|publisher=American Mathematical Society|last=Donaldson|first=James|location=Providence, R.I.|oclc=18191729|isbn=0-8218-0136-8|pp=453}}</ref>
Although Bouchet was elected to Phi Beta Kappa along with other members of the Yale class of 1874, the official induction did not take place until 1884, when the Yale chapter was reorganized after thirteen years of inactivity. Because of the circumstances, Bouchet was not the first African American elected to Phi Beta Kappa as many historical accounts state; that honor belongs to George Washington Henderson (University of Vermont). Bouchet was also among the first 20 Americans (of any race) to receive a Ph.D. in physics and was the sixth to earn a Ph.D. in physics from [[Yale]].<ref>[http://www.ebasi.org/biobouchet.html Biography of Dr. Edward A. Bouchet]</ref><ref>[http://www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/physics/bouchet_edward_alexander.html Physicists of the African Diaspora]</ref>
==Early life== Edward Bouchet was born at home in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], to parents William and Susan (Cooley) Bouchet. At that time, there were only three schools in New Haven open to black children. Bouchet was enrolled in the Artisan Street Colored School with only one teacher, who nurtured Bouchet's academic abilities. He attended the New Haven High School from 1866 to 1868 and then [[Hopkins School]] from 1868 to 1870, where he was named [[valedictorian]] (after graduating first in his class).<ref name="bio1">[http://www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/physics/bouchet_edward_alexander.html Edward Alexander Bouchet Bio]</ref> He ranked sixth in his class on graduation from Yale.<ref name=YaleObit>{{Citation | last = | first = | year = 1918 | title = Bulletin of Yale University: Obituary Record of Yale Graduates | publisher = Yale University | publication-place = New Haven, Connecticut | pages = 919–20 | url = http://mssa.library.yale.edu/obituary_record/1859_1924/1918-19.pdf | accessdate = 4 March 2014 }}</ref>
==Professional life== Bouchet was unable to find a university teaching position after college, probably because of [[racial discrimination]]. Bouchet moved to Philadelphia in 1876 and took a position at the [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia's]] Institute for Colored Youth (now [[Cheyney University of Pennsylvania]]), where he taught [[physics]] and [[chemistry]] for the next 26 years.<ref name="bio1"/>{{efn|The Institute for Colored Youth was later renamed [[Cheyney University]].}} He resigned in 1902 at the height of the [[W. E. B. Du Bois]]-[[Booker T. Washington]] controversy over the need for an industrial vs. collegiate education for blacks.
Bouchet spent the next 14 years holding a variety of jobs around the country. Between 1905 and 1908, Bouchet was director of academics at St. Paul's Normal and Industrial School in Lawrenceville, Virginia (presently, [[Saint Paul's College, Virginia|St. Paul's College]]). He was then principal and teacher at Lincoln High School in [[Gallipolis, Ohio]] from 1908 to 1913. He joined the faculty of [[Bishop College]] in Marshall, Texas in 1913. Illness finally forced him to retire in 1916 and he moved back to New Haven. He died there, in his childhood home, in 1918, at age of 66. He had never married and had no children. He was a Republican.<ref>Frank Lincoln Mather, [https://books.google.com/books?id=tWTXAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA31&dq=edward+alexander+bouchet+frank+lincoln+mather&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZcA-U_KcF6LCyQGk2YGoCA&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=edward%20alexander%20bouchet%20frank%20lincoln%20mather&f=false "Who's who of the Colored Race"], 1915</ref>
The [[American Physical Society]] (APS Physics) confers the Edward A. Bouchet Award on some of the nation's outstanding physicists for their contribution to physics.<ref>[http://www.aps.org/programs/minorities/honors/bouchet.cfm American Physical Society, Edward A. Bouchet Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615071548/http://aps.org/programs/minorities/honors/bouchet.cfm |date=2010-06-15 }}</ref> The [[Edward Bouchet Abdus Salam Institute]] <ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ebasi.org/ebasidoc.pdf|title = EBASI Council Member Initiating Document|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> was founded in 1988 by the late [[Nobel Laureate]], Professor [[Abdus Salam]] under the direction of the founding Chairman Charles S. Brown.<ref>[http://www.ebasi.org/ Brief History of the Edward Bouchet Abdus Salam Institute]</ref> In 2005, Yale and [[Howard University]] founded the Edward A. Bouchet Graduate Honor Society in his name. The current chair of EBASI is Professor [[Milton Dean Slaughter]].
