{{Infobox video game | image = File:Nile,_Passage_to_Egypt_cover.jpeg | developer = Human Code | publisher = Discovery Channel Multimedia | platforms = Macintosh, Windows | genre = Educational, Simulation }}
'''''Nile: Passage to Egypt''''' is a 1995 [[educational video game]] by the [[Discovery Channel]].
== Production == The game was part of a "co-promotional strategy" which involved a [[CD-ROM]] and television program of the same name being released concurrently.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1994-12-19|title=Discovery expands multimedia presence; cable programer to double CD-ROM output. (Discovery Communications to introduce new CD-ROM products)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-15999072.html}}</ref> The game's released was tentatively scheduled for release in Spring of 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Discovery+Multimedia+edu+adventures+to+bow.-a016020641|title=Discovery Multimedia edu adventures to bow. - Free Online Library|website=www.thefreelibrary.com|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref>
== Gameplay == Players undertake an interactive journey down the [[Nile|Nile River]] through [[History of modern Egypt|modern]] and [[ancient Egypt]] on an Egyptian sailing boat called a [[felucca]]. Players explore local culture and interact with customers via [[virtual tour]]s. The player navigates through a series of 360 degree screens, or can also choose new locations via a map. [[Screen hotspot|Hotspots]] on the screen trigger 40 films, 300 pictures, 3.5 hours of audio narration, and text.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pcworld.es/archive/nilo-un-viaje-por-egipto|title=Nilo: un viaje por Egipto|date=1996-10-01|language=es-ES|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref>
== Critical reception == Jaime de Yraolagoitia of ''[[PC World]]'' stated that the game was a pleasant way to learn more about Egyptian culture, and was suitable for all ages.<ref name=":0" /> Lance Elko of ''[[Computer Shopper (US magazine)|Computer Shopper]]'' described the experience as rich and engrossing.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1995-10-01|title=Take a journey through time with Nile: A Passage to Egypt. (Discovery Channel Multimedia) (Software Review)(Evaluation)(Brief Article) (Evaluation)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-17378207.html}}</ref> ''Daily News'' thought the multimedia elements were excellent and complimented each other.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1996-02-05|title=WELL-MADE CDS SPARK INTEREST\Atlas encourages junior explorers.(BUSINESS) (sound recording review)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-83903431.html}}</ref>
The game won the Software Consumer Award for Best Home Learning Program for Adults at the 1996 [[Software and Information Industry Association#CODiE Awards|Codie award]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.siia.net/archive/codies/2015/pw_1996.asp|title=SIIA Awards Past Winners|website=www.siia.net|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref>
